{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-5","id":"msg_01CrjQkDzQpqPNjg74tcUbCf","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Everything checks out. Summary of the fix:\n\n- **What was broken**: Prometheus's ConfigMap (`prometheus-config`) only had a self-scrape job (`localhost:9090`); nothing pointed at RabbitMQ.\n- **Fix**: Updated the `prometheus-config` ConfigMap (native K8s resource, no CRDs) to:\n  1. Add a `rabbitmq` scrape job with three static targets — the per-pod stable DNS names from the existing `rabbitmq-headless` service (`rabbitmq-0/1/2.rabbitmq-headless.<ns>.svc.cluster.local:15692`), scraping `/metrics` (RabbitMQ's `rabbitmq_prometheus` plugin was already enabled and listening on 15692, confirmed via `rabbitmq-config` and a direct curl).\n  2. Add a `rabbitmq_rules.yml` recording rule (`rabbitmq_up = up{job=\"rabbitmq\"}`) so the literal `rabbitmq_up` metric exists, since Prometheus's built-in `up` metric bypasses relabeling.\n  3. Referenced the rule file via `rule_files` in `prometheus.yml`.\n- Reloaded via the existing `--web.enable-lifecycle` `/​-/reload` endpoint (waited for kubelet's ConfigMap volume sync, ~60-90s, before each reload).\n\nVerified: all 3 RabbitMQ targets show `health: up` in `/api/v1/targets`, `rabbitmq_up` query returns 3 samples (all value `1`), and the RabbitMQ StatefulSet remains healthy (3/3 pods running, cluster_status shows all 3 nodes as running disk nodes)."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1467,"cache_read_input_tokens":61775,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1467},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c7528d00-5bf6-4d06-a62a-01b6aebc4724","uuid":"69ed04a3-c921-488c-a6b0-92bcf804a82b","request_id":"req_011Ccar3NMEfYnbWdJu2k2rt"}
